    fullDescription: "Bath, an hour and a half west of London by direct train, is one of England's most beautiful cities and a UNESCO World Heritage Site in its entirety, built from a warm honey-coloured local stone. Its origins lie with the Romans, who raised a great bathing complex around Britain's only natural hot springs — the remarkably preserved Roman Baths, with their steaming green pool and museum, remain the star attraction. The city reached its zenith in the Georgian era as a fashionable spa resort, leaving a legacy of elegant crescents and terraces, above all the sweeping Royal Crescent and the Circus, and providing the backdrop to Jane Austen's novels (celebrated at the Jane Austen Centre). Add the fan-vaulted Bath Abbey, the shop-lined Pulteney Bridge over the weir, good museums and independent shopping, and there's plenty to fill a full day. To bathe in the thermal waters yourself, the modern Thermae Bath Spa offers a rooftop pool with city views. Direct trains run from Paddington. It's a longer day trip than Windsor or Oxford but richly rewarding for its architecture, Roman history and refined atmosphere — comfortable shoes and an early start are advised.",
